#This is the code for generating the simulations presented in the
#manuscript "State Engineering via Nonlinear Interferometer with Linear Spectral Phases"
#by the authors Cody Charles Payne, Elaganuru Bashaiah, and Markus Allgaier.
#The code simulates the operation of a four-stage nonlinear interferometer (NLI)
#with linear spectral phases (time delays). The code can generate simulations 
#of either a grid or high-dimensional entangled (HDE) state depending on the choice of the variable titled grid_or_HDE.
#The difference between these cases is only the sequence of time delays.
#Time delays are chosen for pump, signal, and idler photons individually and
#then summed in such a way that for a given crystal (indexed 'j') 
#the total spectral phase for the amplitude corresponding to pair production in crystal j is (omega_s + omega_i) * (sum of time delays applied to pump prior to crystal j)
#+omega_s * (sum of time delays applied to signal photon following crystal j)
#+omega_i * (sum of time delays applied to idler photon following crystal j).
#The modulation which the joint spectrum receives is then sum_j (exp(i * total spectral phase for crystal j)).
#We generate the joint spectral amplitude in the absence of the modulation term by assuming a gaussian pump profile and a sinc phase matching function.
#We then simulate the effect of loss by assuming that for every crystal with the exception of the first
#there are two interfaces between free-space and fiber at which loss compounds. 
#In the case of the grid state we show the first two signal and idler spectral modes
#calculated via singular value decomposition as well as the spectral state of the idler photon which results from 
#wavelength-resolving projective measurement on the signal photon.
#We show how the modes and this projected state vary with different amounts of loss.
#We also show for both states how the Schmidt number, overlap between the lossy modulated state with the lossless modulated state, and overlap of the lossy modulated state with the unmodulated state
#vary with loss. 

